      <div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Islam_page_design">Islam page design</span></h2>
<p>Hi.  I just want to comment on your edit (by Wikijeff) to <a href="/wiki/Islam_(Bookshelf)" title="Islam (Bookshelf)">Islam (Bookshelf)</a>.  I wrote that from my basic knowledge... it's not an excerpt from Wikipedia... although, besides the part about Islam inhabiting BP in the Library of Congress classification it can all be found in that article.  I didn't want to change your edit but just tell you it wasn't an excerpt so you can do as you see fit. <a href="/wiki/User:Grenavitar" title="User:Grenavitar">Grenavitar</a> 14:24, 28 December 2006 (EST)
</p><p>Since it is an original work i will remove the link. Personally i am not in favor of this sort of praising the Wikipedia, but i do accept other views. This is why i changed one page myself. We should decide which style is preferred by the volunteers. <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 00:20, 29 December 2006 (EST)
</p>
<dl><dd>I have no love for my work.  It was just a silly intro (and I wanted to mention that Muslim theological books were classified under BP).  I'd have no problem whatsoever if you change it to praise Wikipedia.  So, the fact that I added my own writing should not indicate that I prefer it.  At some point there should be some discussion on whether we should tailor the text to talk more about books on the related subject rather than just the subject.  An example would be whether or not the Library of Congress Classification is useful or not.  Would it be useful to mention the scope of the books on the shelf?  For instance our shelf represents, more or less, semi-early Christian views of Islam.  It is not representative of Islamic studies as a whole since most major contributions in English postdate 1923.  I have not fully decided what I think the intros should be--but these are issues that deserve discussion. <a href="/wiki/User:Grenavitar" title="User:Grenavitar">Grenavitar</a> 01:13, 29 December 2006 (EST)</dd></dl>
<p>Original work is original work so no Wikipedia link. The Wikipedia text is not that good anyway. The other pages maily use the Wikipedia definitions out of laziness (im my case i am sure&#160;:).<br />
The classification is useful like any additional information. We are free to add any text to the page we want. The main limit is that it should stay on topic which is Islam books on PG and should avoid too much opinion. Otherwise this could easily result in nasty edit wars. <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 01:46, 29 December 2006 (EST)
</p>
<dl><dd><dl><dd>Some of the bookshelf pages had Wikipedia quotes. Some bookshelves lacked Wikipedia citiations, and I added them. My adding the Wikipedia Citation to the Islam Bookshelf was an error. Sorry. &#8212;<a href="/wiki/User:Wikijeff" title="User:Wikijeff">Wikijeff</a> 18:12, 2 January 2007 (EST)</dd></dl></dd></dl>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Image">Image</span></h2>
<p><img src="http://www.gutenberg.org/files/15658/15658-h/images/img029.jpg" alt="img029.jpg"/>
</p><p><img src="http://www.gutenberg.org/files/15658/15658-h/images/img045.jpg" alt="img045.jpg"/>
</p><p>Either of those image from <a href="//www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/15658" class="extiw" title="ebook:15658">Topsy-Turvy Land</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/File:BookIcon.png" class="image"><img alt="BookIcon.png" src="//www.gutenberg.org/w/images/9/92/BookIcon.png" width="16" height="16" /></a> would work.  I didn't see anything better... <a href="/wiki/User:Grenavitar" title="User:Grenavitar">Grenavitar</a> 21:19, 14 February 2007 (EST)
</p><p>Images of a person are offending for a Muslim so i chose the first picture. <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 13:53, 16 February 2007 (EST)
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Muhammad_vs_Mohammed">Muhammad vs Mohammed</span></h2>
<p>The book title should always be the original one. <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 05:42, 30 March 2007 (EDT)
</p>
<dl><dd>Hmm, did I make a mistake on any of the book titles?  Most English books pre-1923 will use the latter but the modern standard is the former. <a href="/wiki/User:Grenavitar" title="User:Grenavitar">Grenavitar</a> 11:13, 30 March 2007 (EDT)</dd></dl>
<p>No. I meant the comment for the page change. If Muhammad is the correct modern spelling then it should be used on the page, but the book titles using Mahomet and Mohammed etc should stay as they are. <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 12:56, 30 March 2007 (EDT)
</p>
